1. Discrete Time Signals¶

A signal $x[n]$ is a function that maps an independent variable to a dependent variable.

In this course, we will focus on discrete-time signals $x[n]$:

  • Independent variable is an integer: $n \in \mathbb{Z}$
  • Dependent variable is a real or complex number: $x[n] \in \mathbb{R}$ or $\mathbb{C}$

1.1. Plot Real Signals¶

  • plot for continuous signals in Python

  • stem for discrete signals in Python

$$x(t) = \sin(2\pi t)$$

2. Complex Signals¶

2.1. Complex Numbers¶



$$\text{Complex number = vector in 2D}$$

2.1.1. Adding Complex Numbers¶


$$\begin{align*} z_1 = a_1 + i b_1, \qquad \vec{z}_1 = \begin{bmatrix}a_1 \\ b_1 \end{bmatrix}\\ z_2 = a_2 + i b_2, \qquad \vec{z}_2 = \begin{bmatrix}a_2 \\ b_2 \end{bmatrix}\\ \end{align*}$$

$$\begin{align*} z = z_1 + z_2 &= (a_1 + a_2) + i (b_1 + b_2)\\ \\ \vec{z} = \vec{z}_1 + \vec{z}_2 &= \begin{bmatrix}a_1 \\ b_1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}a_2 \\ b_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}a_1 + a_2 \\ b_1 + b_2 \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

2.1.2 Complex Exponential Function (Euler's Formular)¶


$$ e^{i\theta} = \cos\theta + i\sin\theta $$

$$\begin{align*} \vec{z} &= r\cos\theta + i\,r\sin\theta \\ \vec{z} &= re^{i\theta} = r\,(\cos\theta + i\sin\theta)\\ \\ r &\text{ : magnitude (length)}\\ \theta &\text{ : phase (angle)} \end{align*}$$

2.1.3. Multiplying/Dividing Complex Numbers¶

  • Just like an exponential function
$$ \begin{align*} z_1 = r_1e^{i\theta_1} \\ z_2 = r_2e^{i\theta_2} \end{align*}$$ $$ \implies$$ $$\begin{align*} z_1 \cdot z_2 & = r_1r_2 e^{i(\theta_1 + \theta_2)}\\ \frac{z_1}{z_2} & = \frac{r_1}{r_2} e^{i(\theta_1 - \theta_2)} \end{align*}$$

2.2. Circular Motion Represented by Complex Number¶

2.2.1. Geometrical Meaning of $e^{i\theta}$¶

$$ e^{i\theta} = \cos\theta + i\sin\theta$$


$$\begin{align*} e^{i\theta} & \text{: point on the unit circle with angle of } \theta \\ e^{i\theta} &= e^{i(\theta + 2\pi)} = \cdots = e^{i(\theta + 2\pi k)} = \cdots\\ \\ &\text{static} \end{align*}$$

2.2.2. Geometrical Meaning of $e^{i\omega t}$¶

$$\begin{align*} \theta &= \omega t = 2 \pi f t\\ e^{i\omega t} &: \text{ rotating on an unit circle with angular velocity of }\omega \\ \\ &\text{dynamic} \end{align*}$$

Question: what is the physical meaning of $e^{-i\omega t}$ ?

2.3. Sinusoidal Functions from Circular Motions (sin & cos)¶

  • Real part ($\cos$ term) is the projection onto the $Re\{\}$ axis

  • Imaginary part ($\sin$ term) is the projection onto the $Im\{\}$ axis


$$\text{ projection of } e^{j \omega t} \text{ onto Re-axis}$$ $$\text{ projection of } e^{j \omega t} \text{ onto Im-axis}$$
$$\text{Re}\left(e^{i\omega t}\right) = \cos\omega t$$ $$\text{Im}\left(e^{i\omega t}\right) = \sin\omega t$$

  • Animated explanation of
$$ \cos \omega t = \frac{e^{i \omega t} + e^{-i \omega t}}{2}$$

3. Discrete Sinusoids¶


$$e ^ {j(\omega n+\phi)} = \cos (\omega n + \phi) + j \sin (\omega n + \phi)$$

Discrete Sinusoids

$$ \begin{align*}x[n] &= A\cos(\omega_0 n + \phi)\quad \text{or}\\ \\ x[n] &= Ae^{j\omega_0 n + j \phi}\end{align*}$$

Key question: which one is a higher frequency?

$$\omega_0 = \pi ~~~ \text{or} ~~~ \omega_0 = \frac{3\pi}{2}$$
In [12]:
n = np.arange(0, 8)
x1 = np.cos(np.pi*n)
x2 = np.cos(3/2*np.pi*n)

# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.stem(n, x1)
plt.ylim([-1.5, 1.5])
plt.title('$x_1$')

plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.stem(n, x2)
plt.ylim([-1.5, 1.5])
plt.title('$x_2$')
plt.xlabel('n')
plt.show()

3.1. Frequency in Discrete Sinusoids¶

$$0 \; \rightarrow \; \frac{1}{8}\pi \; \rightarrow \; \frac{2}{8}\pi \; \rightarrow \; \frac{8}{8}\pi$$

3.2. Aliasing¶

Aliasing occurs when a system is measured at an insufficient sampling rate. It is perhaps best explained through an example.

In [15]:
t = np.linspace(0, 10*2*np.pi, 300)
x = np.sin(t)
y = np.cos(t)

# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.plot(t, x)
plt.xlim([np.min(t), np.max(t)])
plt.ylabel('sin(t)')

plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.plot(t, y)
plt.ylabel('cos(t)')
plt.xlim([np.min(t), np.max(t)])
plt.show()

N = 20
n = np.arange(0, 3*N)
x = np.exp(-n/N)*np.exp(1j*2*np.pi/N*n)

1) retangular form

In [22]:
# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.stem(n, np.real(x), markersize=4)
plt.plot(n, np.exp(-n/N), 'r--')
plt.plot(n, -np.exp(-n/N), 'r--')
plt.xlim([np.min(n), np.max(n)])
plt.ylabel('real')

plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.stem(n, np.imag(x), markersize=4)
plt.plot(n, np.exp(-n/N), 'r--')
plt.plot(n, -np.exp(-n/N), 'r--')
plt.ylabel('imag')
plt.xlabel('n')
plt.xlim([np.min(n), np.max(n)])
plt.show()
In [23]:
# plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.scatter(n, np.real(x), np.imag(x))
ax.set_xlabel('n')
ax.set_ylabel('real')
ax.set_zlabel('imag')
plt.show()

2) polar form

$$ \begin{align*} x[n] &=e^{-\frac{n}{N}}e^{j\frac{2\pi}{N} n}\\ &= \lvert x[n]\lvert \, e^{j\angle x[n]} \end{align*} $$
In [24]:

plt.show()
